<CaseStudyLayout
  title="Turning Free Into Paid: M365 Freemium Growth Strategy"
  description="Reframing a stalled growth strategy into a personalized upsell experience — and a framework that outlived the experiment."
  role="Lead Product Designer (2-person team)"
  timeline="Aug – Sep 2025"
  tools="PM, Engineering, Content, Research, Data science, Business, WXP product team"
  toolsLabel="Collaboration"
  tags={["E2E User Journey", "B2C", "Freemium upsell"]}
>
  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <div class="not-prose grid grid-cols-1 gap-6 mt-6">
    <div>
      <p class="text-xs font-normal uppercase tracking-widest text-gray-400 mb-2">The situation</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 leading-relaxed">Freemium conversion had been flat for 2 years. Users weren't discovering enough premium value to upgrade.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p class="text-xs font-normal uppercase tracking-widest text-gray-400 mb-2">What I did</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 leading-relaxed">Joined mid-project, introduced a user journey framework that aligned the team, and shipped personalized premium previews under significant eng constraints.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p class="text-xs font-normal uppercase tracking-widest text-gray-400 mb-2">The outcome</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 leading-relaxed">Two waves of iteration narrowed the conversion gap by ~18%. The experiment was sunsetted — but the E2E journey framework was adopted for Copilot trials, and the lead PM specifically cited the "thoughtful E2E user journey" as a model for the business.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>The real problem: premium value was invisible</h2>
  <div class="not-prose space-y-8 mt-6">
    <!-- Text content -->
    <div class="text-base text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
      <p>Freemium conversion sat at 1.5% — below even view-only mode (1.7% vs. 3%). Two years of experimentation hadn't moved the needle. Premium features had a ~6% click rate. Users didn't notice what was locked. When they did click, the upsell dialog appeared with no explanation of what they'd just tried to access. Value was invisible — and so was the reason to upgrade.</p>
    </div>
    <!-- Image -->
    <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
      <img src="/images/Personalized Preview-Problem.png" alt="Language and visual around premium upsell — vague and difficult to discover" class="w-auto max-w-full h-auto" />
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Step 1: User journey framework</h2>
  <p><strong>Framework first, then flow, then feature</strong></p>
  <p>With alignment in place, I translated the framework into a concrete end-to-end user flow: goal signals surfacing the right message at the right moment, drop-off recovery paths built in, high-friction actions (like ad blocking) reserved for high-intent users only.</p>
  <p>Then execution. Some pieces — Interactive Onboarding, the user-intent questionnaire — were already shipped. The remaining work was designing personalized premium previews: a two-week trial of features tailored to each user's goals.</p>
  <p>When a company-wide shift toward AI cut engineering capacity mid-project, I pivoted to Teaching Popovers instead of ribbon modifications — faster to ship, no UX integrity lost.</p>
  <div class="not-prose mt-6 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <img src="/images/Scribble-15.jpg" alt="User journey framework diagram showing preview, trial offer at peak value, then messaging and throttle" class="w-auto max-w-full h-auto" />
  </div>

  <h2>Step 2: User flow</h2>
  <p><strong>Set of fragmented growth ideas into a cohesive end‑to‑end user flow</strong></p>
  <p>The flow was intentionally designed to prioritize time‑to‑value, using user goal signals to surface the right message at the right moment and drive premium conversion. I paired this with clear drop‑off recovery paths and reserved high‑friction actions—such as ad blocking—for high‑intent users who had already formed habits in our apps. The result was a flow that balanced growth outcomes with user trust, positioning upsell as respectful persuasion rather than interruption.</p>
  <div class="not-prose mt-6 tablet:-mx-[10%]">
    <ImageLightbox
      src="/images/Personalized Preview-Flow.png"
      alt="End-to-end user flow showing onboarding, personalized premium feature trial, and upsell moments"
    />
  </div>

  <h2>Step 3: Implementing Personalized Preview</h2>
  <p><strong>Less engineering, same experience — the case for pattern reuse</strong></p>
  <p>With priorities and flow aligned, we moved to unify the ideas into a cohesive experience. Some concepts, like Interactive Onboarding and the user‑intent questionnaire, were already shipped, while personalized premium feature previews still needed to be designed. During this phase, company resourcing shifted heavily toward AI, significantly limiting engineering capacity. To move forward, we leveraged existing UX patterns wherever possible—using Teaching Popovers instead of modifying the ribbon, which carried high engineering cost. This approach allowed us to ship a personalized experience quickly, preserve UX integrity, and deliver meaningful user value despite tight technical constraints.</p>

  <img src="/images/Personalized Preview-Ribbon.gif" alt="Ribbon engineering comparison" class="w-full rounded-lg my-6" />

  <h2>Final Walkthrough</h2>
  <p>Growth is about showing value at the right moment — not forcing an upgrade. This project sharpened that belief with real stakes: a legacy product, constrained engineering, and a team that needed alignment more than more ideas. I am proud of my team that shipped, learned, and knew when the data said it was time to move on.</p>
  <VimeoEmbed id="1172788540" />

  <h2>Impact</h2>
  <p>A 4-month AB test across new markets showed real progress — Wave 1 reduced the conversion gap, Wave 2 brought it to ~18% closed. However, it was not enough to reach financial breakeven within 3 years. The experiment was sunsetted.</p>
  <p>The framework wasn't. The E2E journey and side-pane patterns were adopted directly into Copilot trial and adoption work. The lead PM noted: "all the learnings we can take to other areas of the business like Copilot trials and Copilot adoption [are] a huge positive."</p>

  <div class="not-prose grid grid-cols-1 gap-6 mt-8">
    <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-gray-200 pl-6">
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed italic">Proactive in driving alignment — reaching out to stakeholders, sharing thinking, asking for insights, and proposing solutions all at once. Working with stakeholders who have strong opinions might be tough, but Diana masterfully engages them in the conversations. She finds great balance between 'the business' and users' needs — redirecting stakeholders' thoughts when needed, supporting ideas with research, and making sure everyone's opinion is heard.</p>
      <footer>— Senior Research Partner</footer>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-gray-200 pl-6">
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed italic">The collaboration across teams/disciplines has been absolutely exceptional and is reflected in the thoughtful E2E user journey we delivered.</p>
      <footer>— Lead PM</footer>
    </blockquote>
  </div>
</CaseStudyLayout>

